That’s a fascinating thought, and people have looked at that idea in a few different ways.

If we take your phrase “encoding knowledge into the stars”, it can mean several different things.

1. Ancient navigation and calendars

For most of human history, the stars acted as a storage medium for knowledge.

Civilizations encoded practical information into constellations and stories about them.

Examples:
	•	navigation routes
	•	seasonal changes
	•	planting and harvesting cycles
	•	migration timing

For example, sailors used stars like Polaris as a fixed navigation reference, and many cultures built constellations around seasonal markers such as Orion.

So the sky became something like:

night sky
↓
pattern recognition
↓
stories / myths
↓
practical knowledge encoded

In that sense the stars functioned as a memory system outside the human brain.

⸻

2. Cultural encoding

Many indigenous traditions used the sky almost like a mnemonic map.

Constellation stories often contain:
	•	law
	•	ethics
	•	geography
	•	survival information

The narrative helps people remember the pattern.

⸻

3. Modern interpretation

Today we use stars for different knowledge encoding:
	•	astronomical measurement
	•	cosmic background radiation data
	•	spectroscopy revealing chemical composition

The light from stars carries information about the universe’s history.

⸻

4. Your deeper point

I suspect you’re hinting at something broader.

Humans tend to externalize knowledge into stable environments:

brain
↓
language
↓
writing
↓
monuments
↓
astronomical patterns

The sky was the largest, most stable reference frame available to early civilizations.

Unlike a book or stone tablet, the stars are visible across generations.

⸻

5. The overlooked leap

What makes this idea powerful is the cognitive step:

Humans realized they could map meaning onto natural patterns and use those patterns as long-term storage.

That’s a big jump in abstraction.

It’s the same kind of move that eventually leads to:
	•	mathematics
	•	navigation systems
	•	coordinate grids
	•	modern data encoding

⸻

Your earlier metaphor about stitching and networks actually connects here too.

The stars became nodes in a giant cognitive map humans used to anchor knowledge across time.

If you’re interested, there’s an even more intriguing angle to this idea: some anthropologists argue that constellations may have been one of humanity’s earliest large-scale information systems—almost like a pre-writing “database in the sky.”